# React Purity and Immutability

## Rules

- **Components must be pure functions.** Given the same props and state, a component must always return the same JSX. No randomness, no reading mutable external values, no side effects during render.
- **Components must be idempotent.** Rendering a component multiple times with the same inputs must produce the same output. React may re-render components at any time (especially in StrictMode and with React Compiler).
- **Never mutate props.** Props are read-only. Never modify a prop value, push to a prop array, or change a property on a prop object.
- **Never mutate state directly.** Always use the state setter function with a new value. Never use `state.push()`, `state.splice()`, `state[key] = value`, `delete state[key]`, or any other in-place mutation.
- **Always create new objects when updating state.** Use spread syntax (`{ ...obj, key: newValue }`), `Object.assign({}, ...)`, or immutable helper functions.
- **Always create new arrays when updating state.** Use `.map()`, `.filter()`, `.concat()`, spread (`[...arr, newItem]`), or `.slice()`. Never use `.push()`, `.pop()`, `.splice()`, `.sort()` (without copying first), or `.reverse()` on state arrays.
- **Never mutate JSX element values or keys after creation.** JSX elements and their props are frozen after render. Do not store JSX in a variable and later mutate its properties.
- **Do not use `Object.freeze()` as a substitute for immutable patterns.** Frozen objects throw in strict mode on mutation but do not make data structurally immutable. Use proper immutable update patterns instead.
- **Zustand stores with nested state should use immer middleware** to enable mutable-syntax updates that produce immutable results.

## Examples

### Good

```typescript
// Pure component - same props always produce same output
export const UserBadge = ({ name, role }: TUserBadgeProps) => (
  <Badge variant={role === EUserRole.ADMIN ? 'default' : 'secondary'}>
    {name}
  </Badge>
);

// Immutable state updates - objects
const [user, setUser] = useState<TUser>(initialUser);

const updateName = (newName: string) => {
  setUser((prev) => ({ ...prev, name: newName }));
};

const updateAddress = (field: string, value: string) => {
  setUser((prev) => ({
    ...prev,
    address: { ...prev.address, [field]: value },
  }));
};

// Immutable state updates - arrays
const [items, setItems] = useState<TItem[]>([]);

// Add item
setItems((prev) => [...prev, newItem]);

// Remove item
setItems((prev) => prev.filter((item) => item.id !== targetId));

// Update item in array
setItems((prev) =>
  prev.map((item) =>
    item.id === targetId ? { ...item, name: newName } : item
  )
);

// Sort without mutating (copy first)
const sortedItems = [...items].sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name));

// Zustand with immer for nested state
const useFormStore = create<TFormState>()(
  immer((set) => ({
    form: { fields: {}, errors: {} },
    setField: (key: string, value: string) =>
      set((state) => {
        state.form.fields[key] = value; // Safe with immer
      }),
  }))
);
```

### Bad

```typescript
// Mutating props
const UserList = ({ users }: TUserListProps) => {
  users.sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name)); // Mutates prop array
  users.push(newUser); // Mutates prop array
  return <div>{users.map(renderUser)}</div>;
};

// Mutating state directly
const [items, setItems] = useState<TItem[]>([]);

// Direct mutation - React won't detect the change
items.push(newItem);
setItems(items); // Same reference, React may skip re-render

items.splice(index, 1); // Direct mutation
items[0].name = 'New Name'; // Nested mutation

// Mutating state object
const [user, setUser] = useState<TUser>(initialUser);
user.name = 'New Name'; // Direct mutation
setUser(user); // Same reference

// Side effects during render (impure)
const Counter = ({ count }: TCounterProps) => {
  // These all make the component impure:
  document.title = `Count: ${count}`;
  localStorage.setItem('count', String(count));
  analyticsTrack('render', { count });

  return <span>{count}</span>;
};

// Non-idempotent component
const RandomGreeting = () => {
  const greeting = Math.random() > 0.5 ? 'Hello' : 'Hi'; // Non-deterministic
  return <span>{greeting}</span>;
};

// Sorting in place
const sorted = items.sort((a, b) => a.order - b.order); // Mutates original
```
